# Integrate moth into a Flutter app

Values: endpoint `{{.Endpoint}}` · publishable key `{{.PublishableKey}}`.

## 1. Add the SDK

The instance serves the `moth_auth` package from its own pub repository —
there is no pub.dev dependency and the SDK version tracks the server. In
`pubspec.yaml`:

```yaml
dependencies:
  moth_auth:
    hosted: {{.Endpoint}}/pub
    version: {{.SDKVersion}}
```

Run `flutter pub get`. Expected: `+ moth_auth` resolves from
`{{.Endpoint}}/pub`.

Failure: `version solving failed` → the constraint does not match the
served version. Check `curl {{.Endpoint}}/pub/api/packages/moth_auth`
(field `latest.version`); pin pre-release versions (anything containing
`-`) exactly — Dart version ranges never match pre-releases.

## 2. Wrap the app

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:moth_auth/moth_auth.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(
    MothApp(
      config: MothConfig(
        endpoint: Uri.parse('{{.Endpoint}}'),
        publishableKey: '{{.PublishableKey}}',
      ),
      // Signed out -> the SDK's built-in MothLoginScreen; signed in -> child.
      child: const MyApp(),
    ),
  );
}
```

`MothApp` restores any persisted session on mount, renders the built-in
project-themed login screen while signed out (email/password plus exactly
the providers the project enables — the login UI adapts to the project
config at runtime), and renders `child` once signed in. Pass
`requireAuth: false` to always render `child` and branch on the auth state
yourself.

## 3. Read auth state, act on it

Anywhere below `MothApp` (the widget rebuilds on every auth change):

```dart
final scope = MothScope.of(context);
final user = scope.user;            // null while loading / signed out
await scope.signOut();              // signOut(allDevices: true) revokes all sessions
await scope.refreshUser();          // re-fetch the profile
await scope.deleteAccount(password: '...'); // permanent; re-auth required
```

Without widgets (services, tests), own a client directly:

```dart
final moth = MothClient(MothConfig(
  endpoint: Uri.parse('{{.Endpoint}}'),
  publishableKey: '{{.PublishableKey}}',
));
await moth.restore(); // resume a persisted session, if any
final user = await moth.signIn(email: 'jane@example.com', password: '...');
moth.authStateChanges.listen((state) { /* MothAuthLoading / MothSignedOut / MothSignedIn */ });
```

Sessions persist in the platform keystore and survive restarts; access
tokens auto-refresh before expiry. In widget tests pass
`tokenStore: InMemoryTokenStore()`.

## 4. Call your own backend with the token

`moth.accessToken()` always returns a valid, auto-refreshed JWT. With
`package:http` there is a drop-in client:

```dart
final api = authenticatedClient(MothScope.of(context).client);
final resp = await api.get(Uri.parse('https://api.example.com/todos'));
```

With dio (not a moth_auth dependency — wire it yourself):

```dart
dio.interceptors.add(InterceptorsWrapper(
  onRequest: (options, handler) async {
    options.headers['authorization'] = 'Bearer ${await moth.accessToken()}';
    handler.next(options);
  },
));
```

The backend side of this loop is
[backend-verification.md](backend-verification.md).

## 5. Typed errors

All SDK errors extend `MothException`; catch the specific ones:
`MothInvalidCredentials`, `MothEmailNotVerified`, `MothWeakPassword`,
`MothEmailTaken`, `MothRateLimited`, `MothInvalidProviderToken`;
transport failures are `MothNetworkError`.

## Local development

- `http://` endpoints work (e.g. `http://localhost:8080`). Android
  emulators cannot reach the host's `localhost` — use `http://10.0.2.2:8080`
  there, and allow cleartext traffic in the Android manifest
  (`android:usesCleartextTraffic="true"` in the `<application>` tag) for
  plain-HTTP dev servers. iOS ATS similarly blocks plain HTTP to
  non-localhost hosts.
- Without SMTP configured, moth prints verification/reset emails to the
  server console — look there for the links during development.

## Failure modes

| Symptom | Fix |
| --- | --- |
| `version solving failed` on `pub get` | Constraint vs served version mismatch — see step 1 |
| `MothNetworkError` on Android emulator | Endpoint is `localhost`; use `10.0.2.2` and allow cleartext |
| `unauthenticated: unknown publishable key` | Wrong `pk_...` or wrong instance — re-check both against `moth project get` |
| Sign-in returns `MothEmailNotVerified` | Project requires verified email; the verification link is emailed (or printed to the server console in dev) |
| Provider button says setup is missing | No `MothOAuthAdapter` wired, or native setup incomplete — see [provider-setup.md](provider-setup.md) |
